## Composition Patterns

### Avoid Boolean Prop Proliferation

When a component accumulates boolean props (`isLoading`, `isError`, `isEmpty`, `isCompact`, `isDark`), it becomes untestable. Refactor:

**Pattern 1 — Variant prop:**
```typescript
// WRONG: boolean sprawl
<Card isCompact={true} isHighlighted={true} isDark={false} />

// RIGHT: variant enum
<Card variant="compact-highlighted" />
```

**Pattern 2 — Compound components:**
```typescript
// WRONG: config object
<DataDisplay showHeader={true} headerTitle="Results" showFooter={false} data={items} />

// RIGHT: compound
<DataDisplay data={items}>
  <DataDisplay.Header title="Results" />
  <DataDisplay.Body />
</DataDisplay>
```

### State Lifting

- Lift state to the nearest common ancestor — not to the route level
- If two sibling components need the same state, lift to their parent
- If state is used across many unrelated components, use React Context (low-frequency) or a state manager (high-frequency)
- Never store derived data in state — compute it during render
